title: For Sale:  ALG Defense ACT Advanced Combat Trigger
postcontent: The ALG Defense Advanced Combat Trigger (ACT) is designed for those shooters where tradition, value and regulatory concerns are of primary importance. The pull of the ACT is very similar to a standard mil-spec trigger, however it is sharper and the grittiness of the stock trigger pull has been removed while the traditional reliability of a stock trigger remains. The pull weight is not lower than the M4/M16 minimum weight specification of 5.5lbs. HardLubing is ALG's term for electroless Nickel plating with an integral modifier to the base nickel plate. Either Boron or Teflon is used to enhance surface hardness, wear resistance and corrosion resistance and also create favorable tribological properties of the trigger components. Testing has shown that differential coating of the trigger parts contributes to the sharpness of the ACT's single stage pull. The trigger component is plated with Nickel-Boron which has a high surface hardness combined with excellent wear resistance. The color is a pleasing matte light grey that may be painted on non-functional surfaces if the shooter so desires (such as the trigger bow that is visible outside the lower receiver). The hammer, disconnector and trigger/hammer pins are plated with Nickel-Teflon which combines a low coefficient of friction with good wear resistance. The Teflon impregnation colors the metal a mottled, greyish/green. Parts coated with Nickel-Teflon cannot be painted. Both coatings are highly corrosion resistant eliminating the oil seal of traditional phosphated firearm components.

title: For Sale:  Sig P229 SAS Gen 2 9mm w/ 3 15-round magazines
postcontent:
I'm selling my Sig P229 SAS Gen 2 9mm (E29-9-SAS2B).  This is the "Sig Anti-Snag" model of the P229, so the frame and slide have undergone a dehorning process at the Sig Custom Shop that leaves them much smoother, allowing for a quicker, easier draw (please note that this model's frame does NOT feature a rail -- it is designed for concealed carry use).  The pistol features the factory Sig night sights, as well as the SRT (short reset trigger), which allows for quicker followup shots.  This model features the newer E2 one-piece grip.  I have also installed the thin trigger in this pistol, but the original thicker trigger is included and can be easily swapped out. 

This was my daily carry weapon, and it has been extremely well-maintained.  The pistol was purchased new, and has had a total of 850 rounds through it (no reloads or steel-cased ammunition), without a single failure-to-fire or failure-to-eject.  The firearm was cleaned thoroughly and re-greased after each range trip, and I performed regular full detail strip cleanings to remove any debris from daily carry.  The pistol is in excellent condition, and functions flawlessly.  

Included with the pistol are 3 factory 15-round magazines (MAG-229-9-15-E2), the grip removal tool, the original factory trigger, the manual, the original slide block, a gun lock, and the original case.  

I'm asking $750 for the entire package.  I also have a N82 Tactical Professional holster for this pistol, which is the most comfortable holster I have ever worn.  It features a hard plastic retention section, a leather with neoprene filling, and a smooth suede backing.  The E2 grip texture is quite aggressive, so having a holster like this that covers the whole grip is MUCH more comfortable.  I will sell the holster for an additional $25.  Please send me a message if you are interested, or if you have any questions.  Thanks!

title: For Sale:  MARLIN MODEL 39 EARLY MODEL, NEW - PRICE
postcontent: MARLIN MODEL 39 EARLY MODEL, 22 cal., 24” oct. bbl., casehardened receiver This is a nice example of an early Marlin Model 39. (The "S" prefix was 1926-1932. The "S" referred to the engineering change made to the ejector assembly. The Inspectors "star" was nothing more than a marketing gimmick. It could be found somewhere on almost every Marlin, from 1926-1941.The tang sight is a Lyman #2.) From a collector that sent me more info than I had before the first years of production, serial # S 4420. Early “S” prefix rifles are noted for superior workmanship & fine finish. This rifle also has the 5 pointed inspectors star on the upper tang & the “S” shaped pistol grip. Magazine tube fed lever action take-down rifle, chambered for 22 short, long or long rifle ammo. It has a 24” octagon barrel with what I think is a Lyman #103 tang sight adjustable for elevation , the receiver is case colored. The condition is outstanding , especially considering it is 92 years old. All stampings are sharp & clear, the barrel corners are still sharp, no boogered screws or extra holes & the serial number appears on both halves of the receiver. The bluing shows very little loss & has turned a nice even Patina. There are small pitting issues on the barrel looks like it sat in a gun rack for a decade or two, a few freckles & minor handling marks. The case colors are still visible especially in the protected areas. The stocks are a high grade walnut (2X or 3X?) & have beautiful burled grain. There are no cracks, the wood fits proud to the metal & it has only minor handling marks. The toe has had a chip rounded off The butt plate is hard rubber, checkered & embossed with Marlin.
